r.    &quot;If all parents would send their children to public school, the schools would get better&quot;   We don't want to spend our entire childrens' childhood waiting for that to  happen.  It's called being proactive, btch.  I deplore the sacrifice of my own childrens' future in ways that are not the least bit in the abstract.  Stupidity with an intellectual sniff is still stupidity, in fact egregious stupidity.    &quot;In short, if parents have an investment in the public school system, they’re probably going to make its improvement a priority.&quot;   yes, except things like TENURE get in the way of that happening faster than people growing old and dying.    &quot;She argues that the latter reasons are exactly why everyone should send their kids to public schools: to improve the system for everyone.&quot;   Right.   By the same logic we need to put black students in classrooms with white people in order to get them to learn.   This business of the smart kids pulling up the educational system by its bootstraps is just dangerously stupid.  Yes, freedom of speech.  Just don't inhale.  "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1373" language="en" documentId="3018" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Fritz Wilhelm" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:52PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="18" thumbsDown="0" origId="3018" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1373"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>